The paper discusses the application of evolutionary computing to Multi-Agent Systems (MASs) to create Digital Ecosystems, which suggests a focus on the sub-category of cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems). The paper also discusses the use of statistical physics, automata theory, and information theory to measure self-organisation, which suggests a focus on the sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The use of evolutionary computing also suggests a focus on the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper discusses the construction of an efficiency measure to investigate clustering within evolving agent populations, which suggests a focus on the sub-category of cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing).
